<center><div class="jumbotron">
  <h1><font color="#00BFFF"><b>HOW TO CHANGE YOUR BRAKE PADS</b></font></h1>
</div>

<!--Write in the steps-->

<ul class="list-group">
  <li class="list-group-item">1.) Buy the correct break pads from a local auto parts store. Let them know the year, make, and model of your vehicle.</a></li>
  <li class="list-group-item">2.) Loosen the lug nuts on the tire using the lug wrench about two-thirds of the way.</a></li>
  <li class="list-group-item">3.)Using a jack, lift the car up so the wheel can be removed easily.
<p>â€¢Important: place a block of wood (or other sturdy object) under the frame of the vehicle and behind the other wheels.</p></a></li>
  <li class="list-group-item">4.) Continue to loosen the lug nuts until completely removed. Pull the wheel straight out to remove it.</a></li>
  <li class="list-group-item">5.) Remove the caliper by removing the caliper bolts with a socket wrench.  Then rest the caliper on a surface or gently hang it by using a wire.</a></li>
<li class="list-group-item"></a>6.) Remove the old break pads.  Remember how each pad is aligned and how they each fit.  Use force if needed.</li>
<li class="list-group-item"></a>7.) Attach the new break pads in the exact way the old ones were attached.</li>
<li class="list-group-item"></a>8.) Check the brake fluid level.  Add fluid if necessary.</li>
<li class="list-group-item"></a>9.) Slowly put the caliper back on, making sure not to damage anything.  Tighten the bolds to secure it into place.</li>
<li class="list-group-item"></a>10.) Re-attach the wheel and tighten the lug nuts in a star pattern.</li>
<li class="list-group-item"></a>11.) Start the vehicle and pump the breaks 15-20 times while in neutral.</li>
</ul>

